[[File:Piekosiński - Kamienie mikorzyńskie - Tabl. IV A. Perkunust.jpg|thumb|right|260px|]] '''Prillwitz idols''' is a large number of bronze [[figurine]]s and bronze [[relief]] plates allegedly found in late 17th century. The first publication about them, in 1768, further claimed that the figurines found by the village of [[Prillwitz]] (now part of [[Hohenzieritz]]) came from a pagan shrine in [[Rethra]], a major town of [[Polabian Slavs]], and Prillwitz is the location of Rethra.<ref name=pieko>"Słowo o bałwankach przylwickich", in: Franciszek Piekosiński, ''[http://www.sbc.org.pl/dlibra/docmetadata?id=10358 Kamienie mikorzyńskie''], Kraków, 1896 </ref>
While the story was questioned from the very beginning, many experts believed their authenticity, and disputes about them continued well into the 19th century. Finally, with the progress in research techniques in [[archaeology]] have led to the conclusion that the technique of some of the molds was from recent times, while others, while being apparently authentic, had no evidence of the connection with [[Slavic peoples]]. <ref name=kotb>[http://www.runjewonline.info/p73.html Sfalšowani přibohojo Słowjanow], 2005</ref>
Nowadays [[Slavic neopagans]] {{who|date=October 2018}} insist that further research may confirm their authenticity.
