[[File:Lien2.jpeg|thumb|150px|A Lên đồng practitioner performs in a pagoda.]] '''Đạo Mẫu''' ({{IPA-vi|ɗâːwˀ mə̌wˀ|lang}}, {{vi-nom|道母}}) is the worship of [[mother goddess]]es in [[Vietnam]].<ref>Asian Ethnology, Volumes 67-68 2008 p.305 "mother goddess religion (Đạo Mẫu)"</ref><ref name="FjelstadNguyễn2006">{{cite book|author1=Karen Fjelstad|author2=Thị Hiền Nguyễn|title=Possessed by the Spirits: Mediumship in Contemporary Vietnamese Communities|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wk29gwEr8wYC&pg=PA38&lpg=PA38&dq=ong+dong+nam+temple&source=bl&ots=iiqq8AdjpG&sig=Z1uZ4Y1Bx6mUuI0vuy_ry4ROcN8&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiwvIH7u9PNAhXH2R4KHccTD94Q6AEIHDAA#v=onepage&q=ong%20dong%20nam%20temple&f=false|year=2006|publisher=SEAP Publications|isbn=978-0-87727-141-3|pages=38–}}</ref> While scholars like Ngô Đức Thịnh propose that it represents a systematic mother goddess cult, Đạo Mẫu draws together fairly disparate beliefs and practices.<ref>Ngô Đức Thịnh,"The Cult of the Female Spirits and the Mother Goddesses 'Mẫu'," Vietnamese Studies 121, no.3 (1996):83-96</ref><ref>"Đạo Mẫu ở Việt Nam" [The Mother Goddess Religion in Vietnam] (Hà Nội: Nhà Xuất Bản Văn Hóa Thông Tin, 1996)</ref><ref>"The Pantheon for the Cult of Holy Mothers," Vietnamese Studies 131, no.1 (1999): 20-35</ref><ref>"The Mother Goddess Religion: Its History, Pantheon, and Practices," in Possessed by the Spirits: Mediumship in Contemporary Vietnamese Communities, ed. Karen Fjelstad and Nguyen Thi Hien. (Ithaca, N.Y.: Cornell Southeast Asia Program, 2006), 19-30.</ref> These include the worship of goddesses such as [[Thiên Y A Na]], The Lady of the Realm ([[Bà Chúa Xứ]]), The Lady of the Storehouse ([[Bà Chúa Kho]]) and Princess [[Liễu Hạnh]],<ref>{{Citation |title=Mother Goddess Liễu Hạnh under the View of Religious Studies |author=Nguyen Quoc Tan |publisher=Religious Studies Review Vol. 1, No. 2 – May 2007 }}.</ref> legendary figures like [[Âu Cơ]], the [[Trung Sisters]] (Hai Bà Trưng), and Lady Trieu ([[Bà Triệu]]), as well as the cult of the Four Palaces. Đạo Mẫu is commonly associated with [[mediumship|spirit mediumship]] rituals—known in Vietnam as ''[[lên đồng]]''—much as practiced in other parts of Asia, such as Southern China, [[Myanmar]] ([[Mon people]]) and some community in [[India]]... Although the Communist government had initially proscribed the practice of such rituals, deeming them to be superstitions, they relented in 1987, once again legalizing their practice.
==Cult of Four Palaces== The cult of Four Palaces (Tứ Phủ) worships a hierarchical pantheon of Taoist gods, Buddhist and historical figures. They included: ===Trinity of Goddesses (Tam Tòa Thánh Mẫu)=== *[[Liễu Hạnh|Sky Goddess]] (Mẫu Thượng Thiên) *[[Mẫu Thượng Ngàn|Forest Goddess]] (Mẫu Thượng Ngàn) *[[Mẫu Thoải|Sea Goddess]] (Mẫu Thoải)
===Rank of Officials (Hàng Quan)=== ===Rank of Ladies (hàng Chầu Bà)=== ===Rank of Princes (hàng Ông Hoàng)=== Ten Princes are mythical or historical figures. ===Rank of Gentlemen and Maidens (hàng Cô, Cậu)=== ===Rank of Five Tigers and ông Lốt (Naga)===
